Polio vaccine
Vaccines for any significant disease can take up to 10 years to research, trial and reach the public. It took 47 years to make the polio vaccine, 42 years to make the chickenpox vaccine, 43 years to make the Ebola vaccine, 13 years to make the hepatitis B vaccine, and it took H.P. I.  61 years after first being discovered, Aids has not been cured yet.
 In the last 200 years, only smallpox has been eradicated. Also, no human infectious disease has yet been eradicated, but scientists worldwide are now working to eliminate the Coronavirus. The vaccine has been developed in just 10 months, with many candidates being developed around the world.
The companies that make these vaccines are making various claims about the success of their vaccines.
Pfizer claims to be up to 95 per cent effective in its vaccines. Moderna claims it is 94.5 per cent successful, Russia’s Sputnik V says it’s at 95 per cent, Oxford and AstraZeneca vaccines at 90 per cent and Covaxin being developed in India at 60 per cent.



