Third phase of the trial
All these results have come from the third phase of the trial conducted in a controlled environment, but its success rate will fall when it reaches the general public. Because people are divided into two groups during the trial, half of them are vaccinated, and half are not.
Pfizer’s trial involved 43,000 people, 170 of whom contracted Covid-19, but 162 were not vaccinated, while eight were vaccinated, accounting for 95 per cent of the vaccine.
The vaccine has been claimed to be successful, but its effectiveness was not significant. Efficacy means that during the trial, the vaccine was found to cure people up to 95 per cent. The people involved in the trial are usually healthy. They do not already have a serious illness.
When the same vaccine is given to millions of people worldwide, the real effect will be known because, according to The Lancet Medical Journal, 95 per cent of the world’s population already have some form of the disease. That will accurately determine the percentage of their success in different people and in different situations.





Countries have started preparing to buy these vaccines, but all the nations will provide them to only 20 to 25 per cent of the people in the next year. 



